Animals&rsquo; lifespans can be far shorter or much longer than those of humans. Scientists are researching creatures such as &ldquo;immortal&rdquo; jellyfish and long-lived tortoises and digging deep into genetic codes to figure out why animals age&mdash;and what we can do to improve longevity in humans. Jo&atilde;o Pedro de Magalh&atilde;es, chair of molecular biogerontology at the University of Birmingham in England, lays out the state of aging science.&nbsp;&nbsp;



